g.text: Local Proxy
Public Proxy (boring.news)
Bob is requesting a GET request from
secrets.com/this-is-a-secret and doesn't
want anyone to know that requested it
The Masquerade local proxy will
split his request up into different
requests for example the headers
will be 1 request, the body a second,
and so on.
GET: boring.news/article/xxxxxxxxxx?guid=xxxxx&etc=xxxx
GET: boring.news/static/images/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxxx.png
GET: boring.news/static/styles/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxxx.css
GET: boring.news/static/scripts/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxxx.js
The Masquerade Public proxy will now decode
the requests and put them together to get
the request that bob originally made.
with the original request the public proxy will
make the request on behalf of bob.
Bob
Secrets.com
Secrets.com will get a request from the public
proxy server the same request bob made
except from a different source.
Secrets.com processes the request and returns
a response to the public proxy server
The Masquerade Public proxy receives the
response from secrets.com and encodes it into
the various forms that bob requested for
example hide some data in the png that bob
requested, also in the css, etc, and in one of
the responses will be a map to where all the
data is and what order to rebuild it.
RESPONSE: boring.news/article/xxxxxxxxxx?guid=xxxxx&etc=xxxx
RESPONSE: boring.news/static/images/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxxx.png
RESPONSE: boring.news/static/styles/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxxx.css
RESPONSE: boring.news/static/scripts/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxxx.js
The Masquerade local proxy will now
process the response and rebuild the
response from secrets.com
Bob receives the response from
secrets.com without worries of his traffic
being investigated and if it is investigated
good luck decoding and if it is decoded its
all encrypted anyway.
These requests can be seen by ISP's, Network Managers, Sniffers,
Government Officials, etc.
These requests can also be seen however its
coming from a server that isnt tied to you,
and you would have to identify this server
before hand
